---

# üß† Framework for Deeply Understanding Users

*A field guide for Product Managers to uncover real user needs using Interviews, Surveys, Observations, and JTBD thinking.*

---

## üîç Why User Understanding is the Core of Product Management

> ‚ÄúUsers don‚Äôt know what they want ‚Äî but they show you what they need.‚Äù

As a PM, your **core responsibility** is not to build what users say ‚Äî but to uncover **what truly drives their behavior**, and design solutions that solve for those deep needs.

---

## üîÑ Three Core Methods to Understand Users

| Method          | What It Does Best                 | Risks / Watchouts                       |
| --------------- | --------------------------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| üó£Ô∏è Interviews  | Deep, qualitative insights        | Users may speak in opinions, not truths |
| üìã Surveys      | Broad, quantifiable trends        | Shallow responses if poorly designed    |
| üëÄ Observations | See real behavior in real context | Time-intensive, but very truthful       |

---

## üß† The Product Manager's Golden Rule

> ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt ask users what they want. Ask **why** they want it. Then keep asking why.‚Äù

Your job is to **go deeper** than their surface answers. People will often tell you:

* ‚ÄúI wish this was faster‚Äù
* ‚ÄúYou should add this feature‚Äù
* ‚ÄúI need an app like X‚Äù

But you must dig for:

* üß© What‚Äôs the real frustration or unmet desire?
* üß† What‚Äôs the underlying **job** they‚Äôre trying to get done?
* üí¨ What‚Äôs the context in which they‚Äôre saying this?

---

## ‚úÖ Jobs To Be Done (JTBD): The Core Mental Model

> ‚ÄúUsers are hiring your product to do a job for them. If it does the job well, they keep using it. If not, they fire it.‚Äù

### JTBD has 3 layers:

| Layer                 | Description                                    | Example: Buying an iPhone           |
| --------------------- | ---------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------- |
| ‚öôÔ∏è **Functional Job** | The practical task to be completed             | Make calls, browse, use apps        |
| üíñ **Emotional Job**  | How it makes them feel about themselves        | Feels premium, smart, confident     |
| üë• **Social Job**     | What they believe others will think about them | Seen as successful, modern, stylish |

> üîÅ Many products **win** not just on the functional layer, but by satisfying emotional and social jobs too.

---

## üß≠ Context is King: JTBD is Always Situation-Dependent

> ‚ÄúThe world doesn‚Äôt operate the way you think it should. It operates the way it does.‚Äù

A job isn‚Äôt universal ‚Äî it changes based on the **user‚Äôs context**:

| Scenario                           | Chosen Product | Why? (Contextual Reason)                 |
| ---------------------------------- | -------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| Delhi ‚Üí Agra (student, low budget) | Bus            | Cheap, available                         |
| Delhi ‚Üí Agra (businessman, urgent) | Flight         | Fast, cost not a concern                 |
| Delhi ‚Üí Agra (family trip)         | Train          | Balanced, comfortable, social experience |

Your goal as a PM is to **map context** to **choices**, not just features.

---

## üõ†Ô∏è The User Understanding Framework

Here‚Äôs a simplified, repeatable framework you can use on any product or feature.

### Step 1: Identify Target User

* Who is facing the problem?
* What segment are they part of?
* What situation or context are they in?

### Step 2: Use 3 Research Lenses

| Lens         | What to Ask                                                               |
| ------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Interviews   | What frustrates you about [task]? What‚Äôs your current workaround?         |
| Surveys      | How often do you do [task]? What tools do you use?                        |
| Observations | What do they actually do (vs what they say)? Watch them perform the task. |

### Step 3: Map Jobs to Be Done

| Job Layer      | Example (Buying a Notion Subscription)         |
| -------------- | ---------------------------------------------- |
| Functional Job | Organize tasks, take notes, collaborate        |
| Emotional Job  | Feels smart, productive, in control            |
| Social Job     | Seen as organized, ‚Äútechy,‚Äù or growth-oriented |

### Step 4: Ask "Why?" Five Times

Example:

> User says: ‚ÄúI want dark mode.‚Äù
>
> * Why? ‚Üí Bright screen hurts my eyes
> * Why? ‚Üí I work late at night
> * Why? ‚Üí I‚Äôm a freelancer with late deadlines
> * Why? ‚Üí My clients are in a different time zone
>   ‚Üí **Insight:** This isn‚Äôt about dark mode ‚Äî it‚Äôs about supporting freelancers who work late, across time zones.

### Step 5: Validate with Context

* Would this be true for different user types?
* How does the need change based on time, location, budget, or emotion?
* Are competitors failing at one of these job layers?

---

## ‚ö†Ô∏è Bonus Insight: Power Plays & Emotional Triggers

Some companies have a brand advantage so strong, they **don‚Äôt even need to explain** the product.

* **Apple**: Social & emotional jobs are stronger than functional ones
* **OpenAI**: Releases get viral traction due to trust, status, and curiosity
* **Tesla**: Emotional + social status + innovation perception

> üí• These are **power plays** ‚Äî products that tap into **identity, emotion, and social signaling** better than anyone else.

---

## üìå Final Cheat Sheet: "Understand Users" in 1 Page

| Step | Question to Ask                            | Tool              |
| ---- | ------------------------------------------ | ----------------- |
| 1    | Who is my user and what's their context?   | Persona mapping   |
| 2    | What are they hiring my product to do?     | JTBD interviews   |
| 3    | What emotional & social value is involved? | 3-layer JTBD map  |
| 4    | What‚Äôs their behavior vs what they say?    | Observation notes |
| 5    | What‚Äôs the deeper *why* behind their ask?  | 5 Whys Technique  |

---

## üß† Key Takeaways

* People say things based on **emotion** and justify with **logic**
* Dig deeper than surface-level needs ‚Äî users don‚Äôt always know what they want
* Use the **3 lenses** (Interview, Survey, Observation) + **JTBD**
* Context is everything. Different users = different needs = different jobs
* Build for the *why*, not just the *what*

